Area Forecast Discussion
National Weather Service San Francisco CA
443 AM PST Tue Jan 2 2024

...New AVIATION, BEACHES...

.SYNOPSIS...
Issued at 214 AM PST Tue Jan 2 2024

Patchy dense fog is developing in the North Bay valleys and East
Bay valleys early this morning. A Dense Fog Advisory is in effect
for these locations until 11 AM PST today. Otherwise widespread rain
arrives by late afternoon today. Lingering showers and thunderstorms
continuing throughout the first half of Wednesday before dry weather
returns Thursday. Unsettled weather returns late week and into the
upcoming weekend.

&&

.SHORT TERM...
(Today and tonight)
Issued at 224 AM PST Tue Jan 2 2024

Patchy dense fog is developing with surface visibilities reducing
to less than 1/4 mile in the North Bay valleys and the East Bay
valleys. A Dense Fog Advisory is in effect for these locations
until 11 AM PST today. Tule fog is seen on satellite imagery making
a run for the East Bay, easterly winds will continue to transport
the Tule fog into the East Bay this morning.

Clouds out in advance of the next low pressure system will continue
to move in over the forecast area through morning, then widespread
rain will develop during the day. Southwesterly winds and temporary
warm air advection will result in increasing rainfall rates leading
up to cold frontal passage by early to mid evening. Expect steady
rain developing later on today, rain then turning to showers tonight.

&&

.LONG TERM...
(Wednesday through Monday)
Issued at 224 AM PST Tue Jan 2 2024

Showers lingering Wednesday, then clearing Wednesday night with
patchy fog likely. Dry weather returns Thursday with a high pressure
ridge moving in over the forecast area. Periodic light rain returns
late in the week and weekend with additional troughs arriving from
the northwest.

&&

.AVIATION...
(12Z TAFS)
Issued at 436 AM PST Tue Jan 2 2024

Currently VFR across the region, with high clouds beginning to push
inland from the approaching rain system. Expect southerly winds to
strengthen throughout the day today to become strong and gusty with
gusts up to about 20 knots. Cloud cover will increase with CIGS
lowering to become MVFR into the afternoon and evening hours of
Tuesday as rain approaches. Rain begins into the late afternoon to
early evening and is expected to be widespread, later becoming more
scattered as rain chances begin to diminish into the early morning
of Wednesday.


Vicinity of SFO...VFR through the mid afternoon of Tuesday, turning
to become MVFR in the early evening as CIGs lower and rain begins.
Winds will be strong and out of the south, with gusts up to 20 knots
expected. Beyond about 01Z, winds begin to turn to become more
onshore as the front passes, and gusts decrease, with sustained
winds overnight around 10 knots. Steady rain begin to cease towards
the mid morning of Wednesday, though scattered showers will linger
through the late morning.

SFO Bridge Approach...Similar to SFO.

Monterey Bay Terminals...VFR through the first portion of the TAF
period, becoming MVFR in the evening of Monday. Winds out of the
south today around 10 knots and gusting up to 15. Rain begins in the
evening hours and CIGS lower to become MVFR. Gusty winds ease into
the night, though moderate SE drainage winds appear to return for
KSNS in the early morning of Wednesday.

&&

.MARINE...
(Tonight through next Saturday)
Issued at 902 PM PST Mon Jan 1 2024

Light winds and moderate northwest swell continues. A cold front
will approach the coastal waters Tuesday morning and afternoon,
which will result in increasing southerly winds, westerly swell,
and rain showers through the day Tuesday. The swell will build
through midweek, remaining elevated and hazardous to small craft
through the end of the week.

&&

.BEACHES...
Issued at 436 AM PST Tue Jan 2 2024

A High Surf Advisory is in effect from 10 AM Wednesday to 4 AM PST
Thursday. Expect dangerous wave conditions with breaking waves 19
to 23 feet. Large waves can sweep across the beach without
warning, pulling people into the sea from rocks, jetties and
beaches. These large waves can be erratic and unpredictable.

Remain out of the water during the High Surf Advisory to avoid
dangerous swimming conditions. Avoid going out onto rocks and
jetties as large waves can sweep people into the water, and never
turn your back on the ocean!

&&

